title: For Sale/Trade:  SKS 7.62x39 scoped + lots of ammo
postcontent:
1957 Sino-Soviet SKS.
Milled receiver.
Flat bayonet.
Plus: 400 rounds FMJ ammo

All numbers match, incleuding receiver, bolt, action, magazine and stock.
Bore is in excellent condition.
Wood has my name carved in.
Comes with a 4x30 scope.
Original receiver cover is included, to keep it's C&R status so it doesnt need to be registered in NYS.
Also included a 5-round hunting magazine.

Shoots great; under 3 MOA at 100 yards which is pretty good for an SKS.

Owned it for ~10 years and never had any single jam, no matter what ammo it was fed.

Just to be clear: with the new law in effect, the value of the SKS is that unlike AK it does not need to be registered. As you know it, once you register something, you're on the hook, be it a car or a boat.
It shoots better than 99% of AKs even with iron sights (due to a longer barrel and short gas action alike SVD). Scoped, it shoots about 1.5x better over iron sights.

This SKS can be topped from an open receiver, round by round, or from strip-clips.
Eight old black steel strip-clips are included.


P. S. I did receive many angry emails about me gauging price.
 I'm not selling it to make a quick profit! 
Face it: these crazy prices are a new reality, folks; there is no way back.
If you listen carefully for what Brian Olson said on Talk1300, he's hinting of
leaving NYS... without his support and his stores gone, there's not much left.

NYS SAFE act is here for good, its not going to be repealed even if one million people show up on Feb-28 rally ... it's Albany real-politik what matters.

As for me, I'm selling this rifle to get more into target shooting.

title: For Sale:  1861 Colt Navy Revolver
location: Western Platte County, Missouri, Missouri, United States
postcontent:
This 1861 Colt Navy and an 1860 Colt Army (another listing on Gun List)  have been given to me to disperse from an estate of a close relative. Let me state upfront that I am not an expert on these guns but will tell you what I know as relates to their function and condition. I am taking their values from the Fjestad Blue Book which I have always found to be a solid source. I'd rate this Navy as 10% according to the book and have priced it a bit below that. There is no roll engraving scene left, and what I can see of the the address on the barrel top is "Address Col SamL..."  The serial numbers I can see all match and the 25--- SN would place this gun's year of manufacture as 1865...the last year of the Civil War. The "36 CAL" is quite distinct on the side of the trigger guard. It functions well, with the exception that when the hammer is cocked, the cylinder does not always fall in place exactly as it should, needing a hand adjustment at times. The only part that I believe to be not original to the gun is the screw that holds the barrel wedge in place. While it is not museum piece, it is a very good and serviceable weapon of the Civil War period. I'll take your personal check in payment or any other conventional financial instrument.  Personal check would have to clear. Add $20 for shipping. I'll listen to any offer, if yoiu do not think I have evaluated it sufficiently well. 

Rob Kornacki
US Army (Ret)

postcontent:
These are authentic, black, 30 round Magpul Gen M3 AR/M4 PMAGs with dust covers. They are brand new and still in the sealed package. They are $35 each firm. Call or text REDACTED if interested. I am willing to meet in the Overland Park area for a face to face cash transaction. I am also willing to ship them and accept payment via Paypal if necessary, but you will need to add $15 to cover the Paypal fees and shipping costs. 



The next-generation PMAG 30 GEN M3 is a 30-round 5.56x45 NATO (.223 Remington) polymer magazine for AR15/M4 compatible weapons. Along with expanded feature set and compatibility, the GEN M3 incorporates new material technology and manufacturing processes for enhanced strength, durability, and reliability to exceed rigorous military performance specifications.

Modified internal and external geometry also permits operation with a wide range of non Colt-spec platforms such as the HK® 416 and MR556A1, M27 IAR, British SA-80, FN® SCAR™ MK 16/16S, and others. A redesigned bolt catch notch in the rear of the magazine provides increased bolt catch clearance, while an over-travel stop on the spine helps ensure the magazine will not over-insert on compatible weapons.

Similar to the MOE PMAG, the GEN M3 features a long-life stainless steel spring, four-way anti-tilt follower and constant-curve internal geometry for reliable feeding, and simple tool-less disassembly to ease cleaning. In addition, an included pop-off Impact/Dust Cover can optionally be used to minimize debris intrusion and protect against potential damage during storage and transit. Low profile ribs and new aggressive front and rear texture gives positive control of the GEN M3 in all environments, and a paint pen dot matrix has been added to the bottom panel of the body to allow easy marking by the end user for identification. The new, easy to disassemble flared floorplate aids extraction and handling of the magazine while providing improved drop protection, but is slightly slimmer than before for better compatibility with tight double and triple magazine pouches.

title: For Sale:  1860 Colt Army Revolver
location: Western Platte County, Missouri, Missouri, United States
postcontent:
This is one of two old Colts that I am helping to disperse from the estate of a close relative. So I am not an expert on these handguns and took their valuation from the Fjestad Blue Book...my gun bible. On this particular handgun there is no roll engraving  left visible and the original finish is gone having turned dark and silvered, with some old pitting. All serial numbers that I can see match and the 1355-- SN would place its year of manufacture as 1863, smack in the middle of the Civil War. The only part of the address on the top of the barrel that I can read is "Colt US New York America". I could not describe it as a museum piece, but I am certain you know what other people are asking for such in better condition. But if you want a true piece of American history, below the book value for 10% condition, then here it is.  I'll take any kind of conventional payment with my option to wait for a personal check to clear.  Add $20 for shipping.

Rob Kornacki
US Army (Ret)
